#. type: Content of: <guide><title>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:6
#, no-wrap
msgid "Software RAID in the new Linux 2.4 kernel, Part 1"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><abstract>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:14
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In his two-part series on the Linux 2.4 Software RAID, Daniel Robbins \n"
"introduces the new technology that's used to increase disk performance \n"
"and reliability by distributing data over multiple disks. This first \n"
"installment covers Software RAID setup (kernel and tools installation) \n"
"and shows you how to create linear and RAID-0 volumes.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:30
#, no-wrap
msgid "Installation and a general introduction"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:32
#, no-wrap
msgid "The wonders of RAID"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:36
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The 2.4 kernel has a number of nifty features and additions. One of \n"
"these is the inclusion of a modern Software RAID implementation -- yay! \n"
"Software RAID allows you to dramatically increase Linux disk IO \n"
"performance and reliability without buying expensive hardware RAID \n"
"controllers or enclosures. Because it's implemented in software, Linux \n"
"RAID software is flexible, fast... and fun!\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:45
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"The concept behind Software RAID is simple -- it allows you to combine \n"
"two or more block devices (usually disk partitions) into a single RAID \n"
"device. So let's say you have three empty partitions: \n"
"<path>hda3</path>, <path>hdb3</path>, and <path>hdc3</path>. Using \n"
"Software RAID, you can combine these partitions and address them as a \n"
"single RAID device, <path>/dev/md0</path>. <path>md0</path> can then \n"
"be formatted to contain a filesystem and used like any other \n"
"partition. There are also a number of different ways to configure a \n"
"RAID volume -- some maximize performance, others maximize \n"
"availability, while others provide a mixture of both.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:58
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"There are two forms of RAID: linear and RAID-0 mode. Neither one is \n"
"technically a form of RAID at all, since RAID stands for \"redundant \n"
"array of inexpensive disks\", and RAID-0 and linear mode don't \n"
"provide any kind of data redundancy. However, both modes -- especially \n"
"RAID-0 -- are very useful. After giving you a quick overview of these \n"
"two forms of \"AID\", I'll step you through the process of getting \n"
"Software RAID set up on your system.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:72
#, no-wrap
msgid "Introduction to linear mode"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:77
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Linear mode is one of the simplest methods of combining two or more \n"
"block devices into a RAID volume -- the method of simple \n"
"concatenation. If you have three partitions, <path>hda3</path>, \n"
"<path>hdb3</path>, and <path>hdc3</path>, and each is about 2GB, they \n"
"will create a resultant linear volume of 6GB. The first third of the \n"
"linear volume will reside on <path>hda3</path>, the last third on \n"
"<path>hdc3</path>, and the middle third on <path>hdb3</path>.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:87
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To configure a linear volume, you'll need at least two partitions \n"
"that you'd like to join together. They can be different sizes, and \n"
"they can even all reside on the same physical disk without \n"
"negatively affecting performance.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:96
#, no-wrap
msgid "Linear applications"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:100
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Linear mode is the best way to combine two or more partitions on the \n"
"same disk into a single volume. While doing this with any other RAID \n"
"technique will result in a dramatic loss of performance, linear mode \n"
"is saved from this problem because it doesn't write to its \n"
"constituent partitions in parallel (as all the other RAID modes do). \n"
"But for the same reason, linear mode has the liability of lacking \n"
"scale in performance compared to RAID-0, RAID-4, RAID-5, and to some \n"
"extent RAID-1.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:111
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"In general, linear mode doesn't provide any kind of performance \n"
"improvement over traditional non-RAID partitions. Actually, if you \n"
"spread your linear volume over multiple disks, your volume is more \n"
"likely to become unavailable due to a random hard drive failure. The \n"
"probability of failure of a linear volume will be equal to the sum of \n"
"the probabilities of failure of its constituent physical disks and \n"
"controllers. If one physical disk dies, the linear volume is \n"
"generally unrecoverable. Linear mode does not offer any additional \n"
"redundancy over using a single disk.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:123
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"But linear mode is a great way to avoid repartitioning a single disk. \n"
"For example, say your second IDE drive has two unused partitions, \n"
"<path>hdb1</path> and <path>hdb3</path>. And say you're unable to \n"
"repartition the drive due to critical data hanging out at \n"
"<path>hdb2</path>. You can still combine <path>hdb1</path> and \n"
"<path>hdb3</path> into a single, cohesive whole using linear mode.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:132
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Linear mode is also a good way to combine partitions of different \n"
"sizes on different disks when you just need a single big partition \n"
"(and don't really need to increase performance). But for any other \n"
"job there are better RAID technologies you can use.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:143
#, no-wrap
msgid "Introduction to RAID-0 mode"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:148
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"RAID-0 is another one of those \"RAID\" modes that doesn't have any \n"
"\"R\" (redundancy) at all. Nevertheless, RAID-0 is immensely useful. \n"
"This is primarily because it offers the highest performance \n"
"potential of any form of RAID.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:155
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To set up a RAID-0 volume you'll need two or more equally (or \n"
"almost equally) sized partitions. The RAID-0 code will evenly \n"
"distribute writes (and thus reads) between all constituent \n"
"partitions. And by parallelizing reads and writes between all \n"
"constituent devices, RAID-0 has the benefit of multiplying IO \n"
"performance. Ignoring the complexities of controller and bus \n"
"bandwidth, you can expect a RAID-0 volume composed of two \n"
"partitions on two separate identical disks to offer nearly double \n"
"the performance of a traditional partition. Crank your RAID-0 \n"
"volume up to three disks, and performance will nearly triple. \n"
"This is why a RAID-0 array of IDE disks can outperform the fastest \n"
"SCSI or FC-AL drive on the market. For truly blistering \n"
"performance, you can set up a bunch of SCSI or FC-AL drives in a \n"
"RAID-0 array. That's the beauty of RAID-0.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:172
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"To create a RAID-0 volume, you'll need two or more equally sized \n"
"partitions located on separate disks. The capacity of the volume \n"
"will be equal to the combined capacity of the constituent \n"
"partitions. As with linear mode, you can combine block devices \n"
"from various sources (such as IDE and SCSI drives) into a single \n"
"volume with no problems.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:181
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you're creating a RAID-0 volume using IDE disks, you should try \n"
"to use UltraDMA compliant disks and controllers for maximum \n"
"reliability. And you should use only one drive per IDE channel to \n"
"avoid sluggish performance -- a slave device, especially if it's \n"
"also part of the RAID-0 array, will slow things down so much as to \n"
"nearly eliminate any RAID-0 performance benefit. You may also need \n"
"to add an off-board IDE controller so that you have the extra IDE \n"
"channels you require.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:192
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you're creating a RAID-0 volume out of SCSI devices, be aware \n"
"that the combined throughput of all the drives can potentially \n"
"exceed the maximum throughput of the SCSI (and potentially PCI) bus. \n"
"In such a case, the SCSI bus will be the performance-limiting \n"
"factor. If, for example, you have four drives that have a maximum \n"
"throughput of 15Mb/sec set up on a 40Mb/sec 68-pin Ultra Wide bus, \n"
"there will be times when the drives will saturate the bus, and \n"
"performance will reach an upper maximum of close to 40Mb/sec. This \n"
"may be fine for your application (after all, 40Mb/sec IO ain't bad!), \n"
"but you'd probably have identical peak IO performance from a RAID-0 \n"
"volume that used only three drives.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:208
#, no-wrap
msgid "RAID-0 applications"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:212
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"From a reliability standpoint, RAID-0 has the same characteristics \n"
"as linear mode -- the more drives you add to the array, the higher \n"
"the probability of volume failure. And, like linear mode, the \n"
"death of a single drive will bring down the entire RAID-0 volume \n"
"and make it unrecoverable. To figure out the probability of \n"
"failure of your RAID-0 volume, simply add together the \n"
"probabilities of failure of all constituent drives.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:222
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"RAID-0 is ideal for applications for which you need maximum IO \n"
"performance, since it's the highest-performing RAID mode available. \n"
"But remember that RAID-0 should only be used if you can tolerate a \n"
"slightly higher risk of volume failure.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:229
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you're putting together a compute farm or web cluster, RAID-0 is \n"
"an excellent way to increase disk IO performance. Since in this \n"
"case you would already have an existing level of redundancy (lots \n"
"of spare machines), your resources would continue to be available \n"
"for the rare case that a machine with a failed hard drive needs to \n"
"be brought down for a drive replacement and reload.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><title>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:242
#, no-wrap
msgid "Setting up Linux 2.4 Software RAID"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:247
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"There are two steps involved in getting your 2.4 system ready for \n"
"Software RAID. First, RAID support needs to be enabled in the kernel. \n"
"This normally involves recompiling and installing a new kernel \n"
"unless you're already using a 2.4 series kernel with RAID support \n"
"compiled-in.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:255
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Then the raidtools package needs to be compiled and installed. The \n"
"raidtools are the user-level tools that allow you to initialize, \n"
"start, stop, and control your RAID volumes. Once these two steps are \n"
"complete, you'll be able to create your own RAID volumes, create \n"
"filesystems on the volumes, mount them, etc.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:265
#, no-wrap
msgid "Kernel issues"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:269
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"I'm using kernel 2.4.0-test10 for this series. I recommend that you \n"
"use the most recent 2.4 kernel you can track down, which should at \n"
"least be kernel 2.4.0-test10 or later (but not 2.4.0-test11, which \n"
"had serious filesystem corruption problems). You can find a recent \n"
"kernel over at <uri link=\"http://www.kernel.org\">kernel.org</uri>, \n"
"and a tutorial showing you how to recompile and install a new kernel \n"
"from sources elsewhere on gentoo.org (see the <uri \n"
"link=\"#resources\">Resources</uri> section later in this article).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><title>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:282
#, no-wrap
msgid "Configuring the kernel"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:286
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"I recommend that you configure your kernel so that Software RAID \n"
"support is compiled-in, rather than supported as modules. When you \n"
"type <c>make menuconfig</c> or <c>make xconfig</c>, you'll find the \n"
"Software RAID settings under the \"Multi-device support (RAID and \n"
"LVM)\" section. I also recommend that you enable everything \n"
"RAID-related here, including \"Boot support\" and \"Auto Detect \n"
"support\". This will allow the kernel to auto-start your RAID volume \n"
"at boot-time, as well as allow you to create a root RAID filesystem \n"
"if you so desire. Here's a snapshot of <c>make menuconfig</c>. The \n"
"last two options (LVM support) are not required, although I \n"
"compiled them into the kernel anyway:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><figure>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:300
#, no-wrap
msgid "Configuring the kernel for RAID"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:303
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Once the kernel is properly configured, install it and reboot. Now \n"
"let's track down the latest version of raidtools.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Attribute 'caption' of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:310 en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:329
#, no-wrap
msgid "Installing raidtools"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:314
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Before we can install raidtools we need to do a bit of searching to \n"
"find the latest version. You can generally find the raidtools \n"
"program at <uri link=\"http://www.kernel.org\">kernel.org</uri>. Now \n"
"track down the most recent \"raidtools-0.90\" archive (not \n"
"\"raid0145\"!). Currently it's \"raidtools-19990824-0.90.tar.gz\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><p>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:322
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"If you like living on the bleeding edge (and if you're using a \n"
"2.4.0-test kernel, then you do), you may want to head over to \n"
"RedHat (see <uri link=\"#resources\">Resources</uri>) and snag the \n"
"latest version of raidtools you can find. Currently it's \n"
"\"raidtools-dangerous-0.90-20000116.tar.gz\".\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Content of: <guide><chapter><section><body><pre>
#: en/articles/software-raid-p1.xml:330
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"# <i>cd raidtools-0.90</i>\n"
"# <i>./configure</i>\n"
"# <i>make</i>\n"
"# <i>make install</i>\n"
msgstr ""

